This life—principle must be that con- ception of God's character that made Pharisaism possible. Their God was a God whose favour was conditional upon obedience—obedience to what? If you take a savage and persuade him that God's favour to him depends on his obedience, he will not be long in making a code literal and ever-growing. That is the history of much religion. It matters less what the code is—that is an affair of circumstance and mental development. But in the heart of the prophets God‘s word has always struggled against natural self—love, against national pride, to make clear that favour must be the cause, not the result, of service. Jesus was the only prophet in whom there was no pride or self—love, in him alone this word could come quite clearly—the father- love, emphasised, as it were, towards dis— obedience.
